Inflation in Europe has derailed food
Accelerated inflation, measured in the euro area, is mainly due to the rapid rise in food prices.
In November, price increases in the 13 euro area countries were higher than expected, after an inflation rate of 2.6 per cent in October, an annual inflation rate of 3.1 per cent was recorded, the European Community Statistics Office in Luxembourg said.
Official forecasts have indicated only 3 per cent, says Bloomberg.
Unlike the US, British and Canadian central banks, the European Central Bank (ECB) has not lowered the policy interest rate by saying that the decline in interest rates, along with the growth in commodity prices and the fall in the unemployment rate, would lead to the generation of an inflationary spiral.
The ECB would like to keep the inflation rate below but close to two per cent.
According to one analyst, it is Catch 22 for the ECB: "we must deter" inflation so that we do not have to intervene on this subject at a later date.
In Germany, the inflation rate of 3.3 per cent has been a record in the last 12 years and in Spain it has risen from 3.6 per cent to 4.1 per cent.
Inflation in the euro area has taken off as a result of the rapid rise in food and energy prices.
Grain futures market ratings have increased by 88 per cent and soybean prices have also reached their highest value since 1973.
The price of food oil and dairy products also increased significantly in 2007.
This year, the world price of oil rose by 52 percent and last month, a barrel of black gold cost almost $100.
According to the ECB, in 2008 the inflation rate will rise from 2.1 per cent this year to 2.5 per cent, but in 2009 it will fall to 1.9 per cent.
According to analysts, the 12-month inflation rate remains around 3 per cent, however, over the next 3 to 4 months, the average annual rate will be 2.1 per cent.
At the same time, they expect the ECB to reduce the policy rate twice in 2008.
Gallup reports government crisis
After a long stagnation, the number of supporters of Fidesz (Alliance des jeunes démocrates) increased significantly at the beginning of December. Thus, since 2002, it currently has the largest number of supporters, whereas Gallup (Institute of Polling) has never seen such low socialist support, i.e. 13 per cent.
For the faithful voters, the difference would represent, because of the greater determination of the opposition voters, a support of more than two thirds (71 percent) against the support of one fifth (20 percent) for the MSZP (Hungarian Socialist Party).
According to the poll, the MDF (Hungarian Democratic Forum) and the SZDSZ (Alliance of Free Democrats) are below the threshold of parliamentarians: their support is two per cent throughout the population.
The number of supporters of both parties has increased by 1 per cent among the faithful voters, some of whom are going to vote.
The economic climate has continued to deteriorate from the previous low point, the proportion of those who felt that the country's economic situation was particularly serious has never been so high, it rises to 41 per cent and according to 46 per cent the situation is quite serious.
After the more optimistic outlook of the spring and summer, families are once again more pessimistic about their financial situation.
For next year, the majority of the population foresees a worsening and only one tenth foresees an improvement in the situation.
Last December, 71 per cent of those surveyed, a majority never seen in previous Gallup polls, felt that the Prime Minister was doing his job rather badly than well.
13 percent of respondents trust or trust Ferenc Gyurcsány while 38 percent support Viktor Orbán.
54 per cent do not trust the Prime Minister at all and 27 per cent do not trust the President of Fidesz.
One indicator of the change in the political situation is the proportion of society thinking that dissatisfaction with the Prime Minister can be addressed without a change of government.
While after the riots last October, 35 per cent of those surveyed wanted the government and the Prime Minister to remain in office, this rate currently represents only 20 per cent. The relative majority (33 per cent) believe that the holding of new elections would be the solution to this situation.
On the question of the intention to vote, 60 per cent of the respondents replied that they would certainly go to vote and the additional 20 per cent said that they would probably go to vote.
To make the comparison, for a "legislative election to be held next Sunday", only 55 per cent of respondents would certainly participate and 15 per cent would probably participate. According to current intentions, the result of the referendum would be beyond doubt.
74 per cent would say no to higher education fees, 79 per cent would say no to consultation fees and 84 per cent would say no to hospital expenses.
When we look only at the same proportions among those who expressed their intention to vote in the referendum, 81, 84 and 89 per cent of voters would reject the introduction of registration fees, consultation fees and hospital living expenses.
Auchan is the most expensive, Tesco has increased its prices by almost twenty percent
The hypermarkets in Budaörs' trade triangle maintained the average price increase of 16 percent last year, but this year the VAT rate did not increase.
Article by Napi Gazdaság (daily economy)
This year, in Budaörs' commercial triangle, the usual daily Christmas Basket also increased by an average of 16 percent, a value increase of well over a thousand forints was registered in all hypermarkets.
Prices, which had already "flyed" in the large food stores last December, have not risen sharply compared to the previous high base.
Nevertheless, consumers are obviously shocked to see that items purchased well below nine thousand forints last year now cost more than ten thousand forints.
The Daily Basket in the hypermarkets surveyed exceeded by 91 forints, at least, the psychological threshold of ten thousand forints.
And the highest value of the basket was 10,573 forints.
(In 2003, this value was 6,800 forints.)
Prices for Unicum and live fish remained almost at last year's level, but prices for turkey fillet, nuts and poppy rose sharply.
In shops, the price of flour and bread followed the data of the KSH (Central Institute of Statistics) but, at Auchan, bread was found from one kilo to 139 forints only.
Competition did not lower the price of the product below 200 forints.
It was surprising to see, also in this hypermarket, that the price of the recorded bottle of two litres of Coca-Cola was below 200 forints, so it cost only 257 forints the bottle recorded therein.
However, this year, in terms of Daily Basket, Auchan was the most expensive and Cora the least expensive.
According to our calculations, Cora increased the price of her Daily Basket by 15 percent while Tesco and Auchan increased them by about 18 percent and 18 percent respectively.
By comparing last year's most expensive basket with this year's lowest price basket, we find a 12 percent difference, while the difference between last year's lowest price basket and this year's most expensive basket is 21 percent.
Prices rose by an average of 1,480 forints.
Last year prices rose by an average of 1,206 forints, although the impact of the increase in the VAT rate was already apparent in last year's Christmas prices.
This process made trade perplexed, hypermarkets could not clearly determine what margin to apply to products as they were unable to predict the impact of price change on consumption.
(If a trader miscalculates the rotation of a product, he risks losing a big profit on the margin adapted to the intensity of the trade.)
As a result of the change in the rate of VAT, the price increase of the daily basket has evolved so excessively that the most expensive basket was 1 720 forints higher than the value of the 2006 basket, whereas the difference between the cheapest baskets was only 844 forints.
This year, the difference was not so great as the value of the most expensive basket was 1,630 forints higher than last year and the lowest prices also increased by 1,284 forints.
By bringing the two Christmas seasons closer together, we have seen a catastrophic price increase, in less than 20 months the prices of daily consumer goods have risen by more than 30 per cent in hypermarkets.
(This does not necessarily confirm the KSH data: for some essential foods, the Institute of Statistics has seen a price increase of more than 30 per cent in 12 months.
This is the case, for example, with flour and egg.)
According to the latter's Daily Basket, this seems almost absurd since the price level of this product, already very expensive last year, rose by just over 10 percent compared to the base.
According to the indices, flour suppliers are in a stronger position than egg suppliers because they have managed to get the sharp rise in prices also accepted by multinationals.
In the commercial gold triangle, hypermarkets do not complain, they constantly record good years.
According to our experiences, the majority of customers no longer look at prices in the three hypermarkets visited.
They buy everything in quantity, they take long-lasting food by pallets.
On Wednesday morning important tails were formed at the caisses of the three hypermarkets because the number of customers increased sharply.
However, according to our information, the turnover is lower in the province, many multinationals complain to the survey companies that they do not even reach the expected turnover, not only for food but also for sustainable consumer goods.
Many hospitals save on disinfectants
This year, more than a thousand infections, mainly caused by the incorrect use of antibiotics, have been registered in hospitals.
The hygienic conditions of hospitals, the insufficient number of beds and the overwork of medical personnel do not help to block infections, says the Chief Medical Officer of the National Centre for Epidemiology.
Many hospitals also save on disinfectants
Not long ago an MRSA infection was diagnosed in the trauma department of János Hospital.
Antibiotic resistant bacteria were detected in a man hospitalized after a serious accident.
The patient was isolated.
At the beginning of the year a similar infection occurred in the same place.
The injured person from a serious car accident came out of the hospital but shortly after he had to go back because of an MRSA infection and, since then, the doctors have not been able to perform a major operation because of the bacteria in his body.
Until 10 December this year, 1,094 hospital infections generated by a multi-drug resistant pathogen have been reported to the National Nosocomial Surveillance System, said Karolina Böröcz, Chief Medical Officer of the National Centre for Epidemiology.
To know that it is the number of infections caused by a multidrug resistant pathogen that has actually been recorded in hospitals and for the rest we have no information.
Approximately two-thirds of the infections (683 infections) were caused by MRSAs, i.e., methicillin-oxacilline-resistant staphylococcus aureus.
One third of people carry Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacteria in their noses without developing a disease.
Infections caused by SA (such as angina, tonsillitis, skin infections, traumatic infections) respond well to antibiotics, they are easily cureable.
However, if antibiotics are used excessively or inappropriately, the bacterium, which reacts well to antibiotics, will develop a well-resistant bacterium that will rapidly proliferate under poor hospital conditions.
In cases of temporary or prolonged malfunction of the immune system, this bacterium can cause serious hospital infections, such as traumatic infection or sepsis, on elderly patients with small weights or a weakened body.
According to the medical director of the János hospital, there is nothing special in MRSA infections, these infections are part of the daily life of hospitals.
Above all, we must not confuse the infection with the epidemic, we can't find MRSA only where we're not looking for them," said Tibor Nyulasi.
SAs are resistant to antibiotics.
"These patients are isolated, the healthcare staff put on rubber gloves and protective masks and we have antibiotics adapted to treat them," said Tibor Nyulasi.
A priori, inpatients are examined if they carry MRSA, however infection cannot always be avoided.
The sampling of the sample is not in the mode
The vast majority of infections caused by MRSA could be prevented, but current conditions and circumstances are not favourable in Hungarian hospitals to prevent the development and proliferation of multi-drug resistant pathogens, says Karolina Böröcz.
As this infection occurs mainly in hospitals and in homes for the elderly, hospitals should control inpatients and immediately isolate patients with MRSA.
However, microbiological sampling is not fashionable in Hungarian hospitals.
It should be noted that the National Social Security Fund does not fund these examinations.
Most cases occur only if the MRSA infection is detectable on the patient, said the chief physician of the epidemiologic centre.
The European Union has rigorous recommendations on the appropriate use of antibiotics in human medicine and there are also Hungarian guidelines for the cure of certain infections and syndromes.
Efforts must be made to ensure that antibiotic therapy is targeted, i.e. microbiological examinations should be carried out to prevent drug resistance, but hospitals do not always take this into account.
Microbiological sampling is even more rare in outpatient care and in basic care, Karolina Böröcz said.
Many hospitals save on disinfectants
Scientific evidence shows that MRSAs proliferate from one patient to another most often through medical personnel.
It is therefore essential to wash your hands, wear gloves and protective masks. However, significant deficiencies are also detected in hospitals in this area.
MRSAs proliferate by infection transmitted by inhalation of droplets and by contact. However, due to conditions in Hungarian hospitals, the infected patient cannot always be isolated.
In addition, rooms are often full, beds are often too close to each other, while in terms of epidemics, patients should be at least 1.5 metres away from each other.
Unfortunately, we also see that hospitals, in difficult financial circumstances, save on disinfectants, they lack nurses, there are many patients, so the risk of contamination is even greater, said Karolina Böröcz.
According to Karolina Böröcz, in hospitals where preventive measures are respected, the number of infections is demonstrably lower or the proliferation of the pathogen can be blocked.
Government project against MRSA
The treatment of MRSA infection represents exorbitant expenses for social security funds, which is why we fight this infection everywhere.
In England, for example, the government has established a program to prevent or reduce the incidence of AMRs.
According to published data, this program is effective and MRSA infections show a decreasing trend in England.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) highlights the prevention of the incidence of multi-drug-resistant pathogens (such as MRSAs) and the prevention of hospital infections caused by these pathogens.
The Commissioner, responsible for a fatal accident, was not in a state of drunkenness.
The official statement concerning the fatal accident caused by the Commissioner of the 22nd arrondissement has been drawn up.
It may be excluded that the commissioner of the 22nd arrondissement, who has resigned from his post since then, who crushed a pedestrian by causing his death last Tuesday, would have led in a state of drunkenness or stunned, communicated Friday Attila Morvai, spokesman of the Public Prosecutor's Office of the capital after the relative finding was made.
The finding confirmed the first result of the investigation, which already found that the former Commissioner had not consumed alcohol before driving.
Last Tuesday, the former chief of the 22nd arrondissement police station crushed a 55-year-old man who was facing him when he turned, with his personal car, in the street Kossuth Lajos of the 22nd arrondissement. The man wanted to cross the road by not passing through the pedestrian crossing.
(In fact, the fact that he was crossing the road outside the pedestrian crossing is not a mitigating circumstance, according to the Highway Code, a car that starts a turn must allow pedestrians to pass.)
The pedestrian died after being transported to the hospital.
As a result of the accident, the Commissioner resigned from his position and applied for his retirement because, according to police communication, he was greatly upset by the accident.
The investigation of this case is carried out by the Budapest Public Prosecutor's Office.
Attila Morvai also mentioned that the former Commissioner cooperated from the beginning with the magistrates responsible for conducting the investigation.
Additional €400 million for infrastructure
János Veres, Minister of Finance of Hungary, and Marta Gajecka, Vice-President of the European Investment Bank (EIB), signed three agreements in Budapest on Friday with a total value of €400 million on a credit line to support education, transport and environment infrastructure and energy.
In 2006, the European Investment Bank (EIB) adopted a budget of EUR 300 million for the Hungarian budget financing of transport and environment projects to be carried out from the Cohesion Fund, of which a credit agreement worth EUR 100 million has already been signed by the parties. This time, the contract signed concerns the use of the remaining EUR 200 million.
The EUR 150 million agreement also concerns the budgetary financing of education-related projects.
The EIB has approved a total of EUR 300 million for Hungary, and the remaining EUR 150 million can be used later, following the extension of the credit agreement.
The parties have signed a EUR 50 million contract for innovation, the state budget will use this envelope in the first place in the research and development project to be carried out at the University of Debrecen.
During the negotiations, the metro line 4 project was also discussed.
The parties agreed that they would discuss the possible amendment of the original contract once Hungary finalized the details of the financing of the metro with the EU.
According to János Veres, this could be done in the first quarter of 2008.
Since 1990, the EIB has provided a total of EUR 8.4 billion for the financing of 113 projects in Hungary.
The EIB grants its loans at EURIBOR interest rate, with a grace period of 8 years and without commitment commission.
Bulgaria, paradise of the EU real estate market
The evolution of the Bulgarian real estate market is spectacular, the attention of the whole of Europe is focused on this Balkan country little mentioned in the past.
What, or who bought in this EU market which is always the cheapest but which will quickly become expensive?
Analysis of the Bulgarian division of Re/Max.
Currently, in real estate, Bulgaria is undoubtedly the most popular target in Eastern Europe with its ski apartments and cheap seaside houses.
In the mountains, the most popular areas are Bansko, Borovec, Pamprovo and Vitosa and, by the sea, Albena, the "Golden Sands", the "Côte du soleil", the former Sozopol and Nessebar but more and more people are looking for a building in the Kavarna and Balcik regions as well.
According to the analysts of Re/Max Bulgaria, sooner or later, the central region of the country, namely Veliko Tarnovo, Gabrovo, Elena, Triavna, will also arouse the interest of investors and they are also more and more numerous to buy in the cheap corner of Ruse.
Sofia, the capital, also offers attractive opportunities, the areas of shops and offices promise the highest depreciation rate.
Bulgaria is on the best track to become one of the most attractive golf paradises in Europe and thus be a priority destination, after the summer and winter seasons, also in the other two seasons of the year.
More vigilant investors are already buying in large numbers, for example in the Bansko area.
According to analysts, people buying a building in Bulgaria are at the same time seeking to change their lives, their way of life.
Most buyers are English but others come from France, Belgium, Spain and more and more Romania.
Maltese and Cypriot investors are also present. On the Black Sea and in the most famous ski resorts, we traditionally meet many Russian buyers.
Foreign buyers are divided into three groups, says Georgij Jankov, Regional Director of Re/Max Bulgaria.
People who intend to settle buy renovated buildings, at a price ranging from 50 to 100 thousand euros, or old dilapidated houses, at a price ranging from 5 to 15 thousand euros, which are then renovated.
The criteria are easy access and communication possibilities, the proximity of a large city, shops and generally that of the local doctor.
The second group includes buyers of secondary residences (since last December, Bulgaria is listed among the top 10 holiday destinations in Germany).
The third group consists of commercial investors who purchase in the hope of achieving a medium or long-term surplus value.
The price of the capital's buildings is constantly rising as demand increases.
In the European Union, real estate prices are the lowest in Bulgaria. However, in the last 5 years, they have increased by 21 per cent each year.
The increase in real estate prices mainly exceeds the increase in wages.
Fodor and the Hungarian six percent
According to the communication of Gábor Fodor, Minister of Environment and Water, the meetings of the professionals end Tuesday, yet Wednesday, after the official opening, the negotiations of the ministers on the international climate regime after 2012 will continue.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries around the world will discuss the Bali road map to define post-Kyoto emission reduction efforts until 2012.
At the moment, there are strong discussions on the subject between developing and developed countries.
The United States also reported that, for the time being, it did not want to discuss exact figures, but was ready to sign an agreement on reducing greenhouse gas emissions by 25 to 40 per cent from 1990 levels until 2020.
Another important topic of the conference is whether developed countries commit themselves, outside of emission reductions, to providing financial and technological assistance to countries in need.
An agreement was also signed on aid to be provided to developing countries.
The aid fund defined by the Kyoto Protocol will be managed by a 16-member board of directors, probably under the UN Global Environment Facility (GEF), Piac és Profit (Market and Profit).
The six percent of Hungary
On behalf of Hungary, Gábor Fodor, Minister of Environment and Water, confirms the EU's ambition to retain its role as flagship in global efforts to protect the climate and encourage the signing of the new international agreement before 2009.
The Minister explained that the EU was committed to reducing its greenhouse gas emissions by 20 per cent by 2020 from 1990 levels, regardless of the successful signing of the "post-2012 Agreement", and was prepared to reduce them by up to 30 per cent if other major regions of the world and/or developing countries were also prepared to make commitments tailored to their responsibilities and capabilities.
Gábor Fodor recalled that in 1997 the Kyoto Protocol countries had targeted a total reduction of 5.2 per cent, and all 15 EU members of that period made a commitment of 8 per cent less.
Hungary has made a commitment to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 6 per cent from 1985 to 1987, and our country will fulfil its commitment, recalls the press release of the Ministry of the Environment.
The challenge is high in Bali because the long-term international agreement on climate policy must be put in place within two years, otherwise the entry into force of the agreement would certainly be delayed after 2012. In this case, the commitments to reduce below the values set out in the Kyoto Protocol would not be immediately followed by a new international emission reduction system, the need for which was stressed in the new report of the International Science-Based IPCC, which won the UN Nobel Peace Prize for dealing with climate change.
The reduction of emissions would be delayed and the increase in the average Earth temperature of more than 2 degrees Celsius could no longer be avoided, which, according to scientists, would have extremely serious and irrevocable consequences.
British Army recruits on YouTube
The British Army units make available, on the video sharing site, recordings made during its operations in Iraq and Afghanistan with the aim of making themselves popular.
First, it was the British Air Force (RAF) that became passionate about YouTube: Special Units operating in Afghanistan have been loading video footage of Taliban operations since March 2006, announced the BBC.
These recordings, taken with miniature cameras mounted on the helmet, are controlled at the Air Force Operations headquarters in Kandahar and are then transferred to Londrès or the compatriots load them on the Internet.
The political message is inescapable
Air Force soldiers have already passed 139 sequences on the net through this route and their "chain" has been watched by more than 75 thousand people.
The British Ministry of Defence registered as the Defenceheadquarters in the spring of 2007 and provides videos of operations in Iraq and Afghanistan, while the Commonwealth Office and the International Peacekeeping Forces in Iraq (MNFI) also have their own channels on YouTube.
Mission to Afghanistan
According to the initial objective of the air force, the videos were put online to recruit, and according to the Ministry of Defence, they were also used to make the public aware of the real objectives of the army's presence abroad.
The propaganda published in this way costs virtually nothing compared to the usual advertising of recruitment on television, communicated to the BBC Gordon Mackenzie, a defence consultant, but it also inevitably carries a political message as it justifies in a special form the validity of the military operations decided by the government.
The Americans made a game
The army is bothered because, apart from the carefully censored and composed videos, amateur videos are passed on the sharing site which also present, for example, the death of soldiers: in the "official" propaganda films, a little hypocritical, the officers do not avoid talking about the losses but they never present the bloody side of the fight.
In fact, many videos had already been posted on the web showing the areas of operations in Iraq and Afghanistan that were being carried out on a real mission, but the British army only recently got ready to load these videos.
American recruits a little differently by using the free downloadable America's Army shooting game. In this game the player can put himself directly in the place of soldiers as part of a more or less real simulation.
