The party is not marked in red everywhere
In Hungary, the law defines exactly the holiday days and, around the holidays, it has become common to reorganise the working days, the number of which will decrease next year.
Holidays are not uniform in the EU and the United States either.
Hungarian legislation distinguishes national and state holidays as well as days of rest.
Days of rest are often linked to religious holidays or important historical events.
In Hungary, we celebrate the new year, the last day of the year ending and the first day of the new year are also days of rest, the latter all the more so that the awakeners can rest quietly.
In addition, in one year we have a total of eleven festivals marked in red.
March 15 is a national holiday, commemorating the revolution of 1848, as was October 23 also commemorating the revolution of 1956.
On August 20, we celebrate the constitution of our state, May 1st is Labour Day and November 1 and 2, we remember the members of our family and our deceased friends.
In addition, we have two days at Easter, Pentecost and Christmas.
On the days of our state holidays, national or even religious rarely falling on a weekend, according to the calendar, it has become common to reorganize working days in cases where there is only one working day left before or after the feast marked in red.
It is true that we pay the price for extended weekends by working or going to school on the Saturday before the extended weekend.
For many years, the Minister of Labour has ruled in a special regulation on the days of replacement of the days preceding or following the holidays.
The Act extends to all employers and their employees, to civil servants and to persons working in the public service.
However, it does not apply to service companies, institutions running continuously and in service, by virtue of their vocation, and also for days of rest.
This year, the working days will be changed only around the end of the year holidays: from 24 December, life stops almost all over the country because according to the experiences the majority of people do more overtime or take a vacation they have saved for these purposes so that they can spend the days between Christmas and New Year's Day at home.
Next year many parties fall in the middle or at the end of the week, so there will be fewer changes in working days compared to this year.
The calendar will be reorganized the first time around the Labour Day to allow employees to stay home four days in a row.
Saturday, April 25 will be a working day to have a rest day on Friday, May 2.
Another change is planned for October 23rd: Saturday October 18th will be a working day replacing Friday 24.
On the other hand, next year, the end of the year will be marked by the holidays because from 24 December everyone will take a non-stop break even if New Year's Day falls on a Wednesday.
