Banks want to solve the crisis
The US Federal Reserve Bank, the European Central Bank and the English, Swiss and Canadian central banks have decided to fight the financial market crisis together.
More than one hundred billion dollars will be invested in money markets through auctions.
It will be for banks to sell, through an auction system, the interest rates at which they are willing to borrow money.
For example, the US Fed will auction $40 billion and, in addition, will provide $24 billion to the European and Swiss Central Banks.
This is the first time since the attacks of 11 September that the central banks of individual states have decided to take action at this concerted point, aimed at preventing or even reducing the effects of the financial crisis.
"This approach tends to solve the major problems of the economy, namely the growing lack of free capital that banks could lend," wrote Bernard Baumohl of the consulting company Economic Outlook Group in his report to clients.
"The concerted action of the Central Banks has reduced the likelihood of a recession in the United States from 65 per cent to about 50 per cent," Baumohl added in his report.
Banks have already lost $60 billion due to unreimbursed loans, especially in the United States.
Analysts are still waiting for further losses in billions.
"If the central banks have chosen this approach, it is because they have to really understand what can still happen," says the chief economist of ABN Amro Kieran Davies.
"It seems that the situation is really bad," he adds.
Central banks are concerned that if banks themselves have difficult access to loans, they will lend more expensively to their customers.
This would reduce consumption and plunge the U.S. economy into a recession that could affect global economic growth.
The central banks made this choice after the interbank rate of Londrès, called LIBOR, used to borrow on the interbank market, was not reduced.
This meant that banks still feared mutual borrowing, despite the fact that the U.S., Canadian and English central banks had repeatedly decreased their interest rates in the fall.
"This will have the same effect as a further reduction in interest rates," said Reuters Greg Salvaggio of Tempus Consulting.
