A heavy memory
After more than 60 years of confidentiality, the Nazi archives of Bad Arolsen, which trace the fates of 17.5 million victims of the Hitler regime, are in free access.
The 47 million archival documents, stored on 27 km of linear in Bad Arolsen (Hesse), were so far only available for "humanitarian" purposes, i.e. individually and nominally, at the request of a former victim or his successors.
The eleven states in charge of their management - including Germany, France, Israel and the United States - agreed in May 2006 to open them to researchers and historians.
As the process of ratification of the Agreement by all States has been completed, the opening of the Agreement has been effective since yesterday.
Sensitive information
The access of historians to Bad Arolsen will enable research to be carried out "in particular on the movement of prisoners, the population of the camps and the state of health of forced workers", explains Reto Meistern, the director of the archives run by the International Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC).
Until recently, several States, including Germany, opposed the public opening of these nominative documents because of the sensitivity of certain information.
Like the supposed homosexuality or mental disability of some victims of deportation.
The records of the concentration camps or arrest warrants issued by the Gestapo had been collected after war for a practical purpose: to find civilians deported or subjected to compulsory work and, possibly, to provide proof of their internment, in order to pave the way for their compensation.
Even today in Bad Arolsen, more than 300 permanent employees deal with tens of thousands of individual requests.
However, for part of the scientific community, access to Bad Arolsen is of limited interest.
"There is nothing fundamentally new to expect from these documents," said Professor Wolfgang Benz, Director of the Anti-Semitism Research Centre at Technische Universität Berlin in 2006.
