What kind of insurance does it fit me?
Motor vehicle insurance, which covers the driver in the face of possible losses, involves a significant expense which will depend on various factors, such as age, sex, seniority of the driver's licence, civil status, type of vehicle to be insured or the use of the vehicle, among others.
Having a car is the main one.
Yes, escoger el seguro de automóvil adecuado es incluso más difícil que elegir el modelo de vehículo.
And it's that, choosing the right car insurance, is even more difficult than choosing the model of the vehicle.
Car insurance is an agreement between an insurance company and the insurer.
This compromise is achieved through an insurance contract, which establishes that the company receives the value of the premium awarded and in return becomes liable for the obligation to pay compensation in the event of a claim.
The premium is the price of insurance, which takes into account various factors, such as age, sex, seniority of the driver's licence, marital status, type of vehicle to be insured or use, among others.
Insurance companies set their prices based on statistics, so that the higher the probability of an accident, the higher the rate to be paid.
This is why people over the age of 25 and women have to pay lower premiums, since statistics show that these people have a lower claim rate due to their caution.
Similarly, using censuses, the companies concluded that married people tend to have fewer accidents than single drivers.
The use of the vehicle will affect the frequency and thus the likelihood of an accident.
By increasing frequency the probability increases.
Many of the variables that insurers consider when determining the price of the premium.
That's why the driver needs to study the situation carefully in order to choose the car insurance that best fits his profile.
Here we will present the most significant variables when choosing one or the other type of insurance, so that it, in addition to adapting to the characteristics of the insurer, offers a reasonable price.
Young people under 25 years of age face various disadvantages when entering into an insurance contract at an accessible price, as may be the low level of driving experience and seniority of the driver's licence.
Although the ideal way to be well-insured is to provide insurance at all risk, other, more cost-effective options exist.
The most forward-looking drivers can opt for free-of-charge all-risk insurance, so that they get insurance coverage at all risks but at a more accessible price.
This form of agreement implies that the customer pays part of the claim amount.
"The part of the amount of the loss paid by the customer will be determined on the basis of the value of the premium, which will be higher the lower the amount," says Luis Noguera, the Spanish head of First Europa, an online insurance mediator.
Another option is extended third-party insurance, so that the customer provides protection to deal with damage caused to third parties, but by those caused on his own car.
In addition, it would be covered against theft, fires and loss of the vehicle.
A piece of advice.
If you are under the age of 25 try to be careful and avoid claims as much as possible, since this will affect the bonus, which may reduce the price of insurance in the future.
A bonus is a reduction in the company's basic rate.
On the contrary, a penalty is an increase in the basic tariff.
"The bonuses and penalties will depend on the company and the company's profit.
If the company has had a good year it will be able to afford to increase the bonuses, " clarified Noguera.
Beyond the age of 25 it becomes easier for drivers to enter into a contract with insurance, since the loss rate is reduced thanks to the accumulated experience.
It is for this reason that it is preferable to choose a risk insurance with franchise.
"Normally, young people cannot take advantage of the experience acquired after an accident", says the director of the European company in Spain and adds that the majority of accidents occur during the second year of driving, once the 'fear of the novice' has passed.
However, if the client is married but does not yet have children it is preferable for him to negotiate insurance at all risk, as long as his economic situation allows him to do so.
Marriages with children are considered by insurers to be the persons with the lowest claim rate, because the increases will be lower.
In this case the best insurance would be insurance at any risk with deductible (may be 300 euros), or extended third-party insurance from the third year of life of the vehicle when the insured has a high level of bonus.
"They have a more relaxed driving and they have greater purchasing power to afford the luxury of taking on a larger amount of franchises," judge Luis Noguera.
For pensioners, deductible risk insurance is preferable (i.e. 150 euros) or extended third-party insurance when the insurer has a high level of premium.
It has to be said that motor insurance is something important, not only because it covers the driver in the face of possible losses, but also because it represents a significant expense, that is why it is essential to properly study the insurance that suits us most according to our personal situation.
