Venus' climate could reveal the future of the Earth.
Scientists yesterday said Venus was certainly a pleasant planet to live in.
Data from the European ship in orbit have shown that the planet is certainly twice as small as the Earth, contrary to what was thought before.
Venus is the planet closest to Earth.
These two worlds are practically the same size, with similar orbits, although Venus is closer to the Sun.
Scientists now believe that billions of years ago Venus may have had conditions similar to those on Earth, and may even have been habitable.
But the greenhouse effect due to carbon dioxide, atmospheric erosion due to solar radiation combined with slower rotation has led Venus to another kind of evolution.
Today the planet is deprived of water, is ravaged by hurricanes and lightning storms and has a temperature surface warm enough to melt lead.
The discoveries of Venus Express, the probe of the European Space Agency, which studied the planet for a year, offer a sad vision of the potential future of the Earth due to catastrophic changes in the climate.
Professor Fred Taylor of the Department of Physics at Oxford University, one of the leaders of the Venus Express mission, said: "We are beginning to understand why Venus' climate is so different from Earth's, although the planets themselves are practically similar.
"Our new data allow us to establish a scenario that billions of years ago, Venus would have been originally identical to the Earth, perhaps even with a habitable surface."
