Venus is the Earth's infernal twin.
Despite its hostile atmosphere to life, Venus looks more like the Earth than we thought until now: the European space probe "Venus Express" has discovered lightnings in the atmosphere and wind whirlwinds at the poles, similar to those that appear in winter on Earth.
For almost three decades, scientists have assumed that there is lightning on Venus.
The European probe "Venus Express" has now proved this - it has detected electromagnetic waves at the limit of the atmosphere: lightnings on Venus burst at a height of about 56 kilometers of cloud, reports Christopher Russell of the University of California in Los Angeles in the scientific magazine "Nature".
According to the famous theory of cyprin, lightnings would have made life appear on Earth: the storm would have stimulated reactions in the oceans that led to the formation of amino acids, the corner stone of life.
This is not the case on Venus: "If life has been there, it must have been at a very ancient date in history," says Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institution in Washington.
Today there should be little living things on Venus' surface: the atmosphere is about a hundred times denser than on Earth, sometimes there are temperatures of 500 degrees.
"Venus may be Earth's infernal twin, but she remains a twin," said Russell.
Why Venus, which looks so much like the Earth in mass and dimensions, has been struck by such a different evolution, is the fundamental question of the ASE mission.
The departure of "Venus Express" in November 2005 was an important step in Venusian research, since no more probes had been on their way to explore this planet since the 1990s.
In the opinion of the researchers, the most recent research results which have now been presented in several articles of "Nature" do not only underline the singularity of Venus within the solar system.
They also show that there are more things in common with the Earth on our neighbouring planet than they were supposed to be at first sight.
Thus the researchers found, in addition to the wind whirlwinds already known at the North Pole, a whirlwind of clouds at the South Pole, which rotates even faster.
The phenomenon recalls the air currents in the terrestrial hemispheres in winter, writes a team of researchers around Giuseppe Piccioni of the Istituto di Astrofisica Spaziale e Fisica Cosmica Italian.
The second planet of the solar system has almost the same mass as the Earth and is, with a diameter of 12,100 kilometers, almost as large.
The planet called evening or morning star revolves around the sun in just 225 days.
However, it turns much more slowly on itself: a Venetian day lasts 243 Earth days.
Although Venus, with surface temperatures of 460 degrees Celsius and a pressure of 92 bar, hardly reminds the Earth, scientists assume that the two planets have formed under similar conditions.
Of the two, the water accumulated and remained on Earth in the form of oceans, but was lost in space on Venus.
And while carbon dioxide has fixed itself to Earth as carbonate, it forms the bulk of the atmosphere on Venus.
