It's not Warhols' crates.
Whoever connects the Swedish concepts with the wooden case, thinks of Ikea, but not Andy Warhol.
Or maybe?
At the moment, wooden cases made in Sweden cast shadows on Warhol's list of works.
A large part of the ninety Brillo-Boxes of "Stockholm Type" listed there are counterfeits.
After the Swedish newspaper "Expressen" questioned a few months ago the authenticity of Andy Warhol's 1968 Brillo-Boxes, the internal research of the Stockholm Moderna Museet now leads to a disillusioning result: the six "Brillo-Boxes", which the former director of the Pontus Hulten Museum gave in 1995 to the Moderna Museet, are copies - as well as a large part of the other hundreds of Brillo-Boxen of "Stockholm Type", which circulate on the international art market.
Ancient history is entangled, a disconcerting chain of artistic and curatorical productions.
In 1964 Warhol created his first "Brillo-Boxes" in New York, painted wooden cases, based on the red-blue-white design of the "Brillo" powdered soap cartons.
An exhibition of his work at the Moderna Museet presented in 1968 - with the agreement of Warhol - hundreds of Brillo boxes made of cardboard: These did not come (for financial reasons) from Warhol, but had been delivered directly from the Brillo cardboard factory.
These were not works of art, but rather their models, exhibition samples.
At the same time, Warhol had given permission in 1968 to have some Brillo wooden cases produced in Sweden, which were not exposed to the Moderna Museet.
Witnesses of the time speak today of about fifteen wooden cases that at the time would have entered the history of art and auction, as the original Brillo-Boxes of Andy Warhol authorized, with the name "Stockhol type".
Some of them reached more than $100,000 in auctions.
The problem now is that the legendary director of the Pontus Hultén Museum wrongly later claimed that about a hundred wooden cases had been produced and exhibited in Sweden in 1968, which Warhol would then have given him.
In fact, the 105 cases of Hulten were produced in Malmö in 1990 only, for an exhibition in St Petersburg.
By that date, Warhol had already been dead for three years.
Lars Byström, chief curator of the Moderna Museet, examined, next to the six Brillo-Boxes of the museum, three other Swedish private collections, two of which were made in Stockholm in 1968: their laminate panels were first printed and sanded, then applied with a brush of white oil paint.
The texture of the copies that date back to 1990 reveals, on the contrary, that the paint was directly applied without a layer of background on the laminate panels, using a roller of paint - moreover it is not an oil painting, but an acrylic.
"These crates have not been authorized by the artist and should be removed from the official list of Andy Warhol's Brillo-Boxes", suggests the director of Moderna Museet, Lars Nittve: "If the 'Andy Warhol Art Authentication Board' in New York does not come another decision, the Moderna Museet will classify the six crates in its collection as copies/exhibition material."
Already in July the Authentication Board of course announced that it would investigate the "heavy accusations" that will be raised in the case of powdered soap cases.
But since then we've had an inexorable silence there.
Manila's Rebellious Soldiers Give Up
In the Philippines, the rebel soldiers gave up, the same ones who had broken into a hotel in Manila, and who had demanded the withdrawal of President Gloria Macapagal Arroyo.
Chief Antonio Trillanes, who accused the President of corruption and electoral fraud, told reporters in the hotel that he could not answer for any bloodshed.
The soldiers loyal to power had shortly before stormed the hotel with tear gas.
The two dozen soldiers had fallen into the building for hours.
About half of them were in court on Wednesday because of a failed coup attempt in 2003 - among them Trillanes.
He took advantage of the audience to suddenly eclipse himself with about 30 sympathizers.
The military police officers, who normally had to monitor them, had apparently deserted in his favour and joined his mutiny.
They entered the Peninsula Hotel and demanded the withdrawal of President Gloria Macapagal Arroyo.
The loyal troops closed the area around the respectable hotel.
The President convened an urgent meeting of the Security Cabinet.
The National Security Adviser Norberto Gonzales condemned the soldiers' actions.
"People have had enough," Trillanes said.
"We call on people to join us."
General Danilo Lim, who was in command before the Scouts Rangers elite unit, said that other units in the army wanted to join the march soon.
The regime's critics had called for a major demonstration against the President on Wednesday.
His government has been surrounded for months by accusations of corruption.
The finance district of Manila was already the scene of the attempted mutiny of about 200 members of the army against Arroyo since 2003.
The insurrection broke almost 24 hours after the army refused to join.
Since 1986 there have already been at least seven coup attempts against democratically elected governments in the Philippines.
United Internet becomes a main shareholder of Versatel.
United Internet has secured a stake of more than 20 per cent in Versatel's telecommunications company.
The average price per share is 14.46 euros, as the company communicated on Wednesday.
Only 20.05 per cent of the share capital would be held.
We'd already speculated about a buy-back before.
The option would remain open to further increase participation in Versatel.
With this step we are seeking to accelerate the consolidation of the German market for DSL, United Internet said.
Just before, assumptions had already been made on Wednesday about an entry, after the bank Berenberg increased its participation in the Düsseldorf network operator from 5 per cent to 15.1 per cent.
The credit institution would only hold the money for a third part, it is said on the market.
The day before, United Internet had already acquired a stake of nearly 10 percent in the mobile phone company Drillisch.
As part of a capital increase, Drillisch has placed 17.4 million new shares worth EUR 106.4 million on the Stock Exchange.
United Internet bought 5.15 million euros for 31.1 million euros.
In addition, the companies have opened negotiations on cooperation in the marketing of DSL products and mobile telephony.
"We are strengthening our partnership," said a spokesperson for United Internet.
Both companies founded the MSP holding company in order to absorb the competitor Freenet.
For the time being, the two companies want to feel satisfied with their ten percent stake in Freenet, and not to use their additional 18.49 percent right to endorse at Freenet, said United Internet on Thursday.
The two companies would, however, be left open all the options, particularly to increase participation in the Freenet SA, we learned.
Negotiations between United Internet and Freenet on a strategic partnership had ended in mid-October.
The still difficult to predict poker on Freenet, which has been going on for months, is part of the consolidation of the German telecom market.
Freenet had at the end of the third quarter 2.9 million customers bound by a mobile phone contract and 1.27 million DSL customers and full subscriptions.
United Internet Holding and Drillisch had to date a direct stake in Freenet of 6.01 percent.
It was now agreed that Drillisch would bring about an additional four percent.
The right to purchase the 18.49 percent of the investment company Vatas had already been decided in August.
